>>You should learn and understand your companyís strategy so that:<<
( ) You know when to buy or sell its stock. {{ Trading based on insider knowledge is illegal. How can knowledge of the companyís strategy help you at work?}}
(x) You can align your efforts with it and ìswim downstream.î {{Strategy will have an impact on you through the decision-making guidance, particularly in the investment of resources. By aligning your efforts, and ìswimming downstreamî (i.e. with the current, not against it) you will have an easier time getting support for your ideas.}}
( ) You can sound knowledgeable to your peers. {{  This is not the main advantage. How can knowledge of the companyís strategy help you at work?}}
( ) You can challenge it and ìswim upstream.î {{  Usually you want it to be easier to get support for your ideas ñ not harder. Strategy impacts you through the decision-making guidance, particularly in the investment of resources. }}
||How can knowledge of the companyís strategy help you at work? Note that strategy will have an impact on you through the decision-making guidance, particularly in the investment of resources.||

>> Which phase of the strategy process deals with performing internal and external scrutiny (typically using SWOT)?<<
( ) Creating the mission {{The Mission is usually already set when as the first step, and before a very detailed internal or external scrutiny is performed.}}
( ) Defining the scope {{Scope is defined soon after Mission, and may be based on the previous cycleís internal/external scrutiny, but is usually performed before this step in the current cycle.}}
(x) Choosing/ Identifying a competitive advantage {{Correct! Internal and External scrutiny is performed to be able to evaluate competitive options.}}
( ) Defining action programs {{Action programs can usually only be identified after the analysis required to frame strategy and choose among competitive options is completed.}}
( ) Setting resource prioritization guidance {{This is the last step of translating strategy into decision guidance, and is performed well after the analysis of internal and external environment.}}

>>To whom can a SWOT analysis apply? Choose the <b>best</b> answer.<<
( ) A private company {{A SWOT may apply to a company, but may also apply to others on this list. So it is not the best answer in this case.}}
( ) A team within a company {{A SWOT may apply to a team within a company, but may also apply to others on this list. So it is not the best answer in this case.}}
(x) Any organization in a competitive environment {{Correct! This is the best, most general choice since SWOT can apply to any kind of organization as long as there are competitive options to choose from.}}
( ) A regulatory body {{Typically, a regulatory body does not need to make competitive decisions. So, a SWOT is unlikely to be applicable for such a group.}}
( ) Any of the above {{Some of the choices may not have SWOT applicable. Consider whether there is any competitive decision that needs to be made.}}

While conducting a SWOT analysis, how would you distinguish between weaknesses and threats? 
( ) Weaknesses are known; threats are unknown. {{-	Threats may be known, and if anything is unknown it will typically not show up in SWOT. An uncertain threat or weakness may be considered if there is good reason to believe it exists.}}
(x) Weaknesses are internal to the team; threats are external to the team. {{-	Strengths and Weaknesses are revealed by internal scrutiny, Opportunities and threats are revealed by external scrutiny}}
( ) Weaknesses are addressable with a strategic decision, but threats cannot be addressed. {{-	Threats can also be addressed by selecting a competitive option that neutralizes them.}}
( ) Weaknesses are caused by a lack of motivation or capability; threats are illegal actions made by the competitor. {{-	Weaknesses are not simply personal limitations, but any disadvantage internal to the team being analyzed (e.g. resources, market position etc.). Threats are simply things in the external environment that threaten success, and hence need not be illegal.}}

Consider the following sources of information when filling out a SWOT. What would you hope to discover using them?


>>I.	Benchmarking performance <<
[[
(Strengths or Weaknesses) {{Correct! Benchmarking performance is part of internal scrutiny and hence reveals Strengths and Weaknesses.}}
Opportunities or Threats {{Benchmarking performance is a form of internal scrutiny since you are comparing the performance of the group to a standard. Opportunities and Threats are revealed by external scrutiny.}}
]]

>>II.	Assessing the available resources <<
[[
(Strengths or Weaknesses) {{Correct! Assessing available resources is part of internal scrutiny and hence reveals Strengths and Weaknesses.}}
Opportunities or Threats {{Assessing available resources is a form of internal scrutiny since you are assessing something internal to the team. Opportunities and Threats are revealed by external scrutiny.}}
]]

>>III.	Independent (third-party) analyses of the industry<<
[[
Strengths or Weaknesses {{Correct! Industry analyses are part of external scrutiny and hence reveal Opportunities and Threats.}}
(Opportunities or Threats) {{Industry analysis is a form of external scrutiny since you are studying the competitive environment. Strengths and Weaknesses are revealed by internal scrutiny.}}
]]


>>IV.	Information about competitor or supplier actions<<
[[
Strengths or Weaknesses {{Correct! Competitive or supplier intelligence is part of external scrutiny and hence reveals Opportunities and Threats.}}
(Opportunities or Threats) {{Competitive or supplier intelligence is a form of external scrutiny since you are looking at the actions of other players in the industry. Strengths and Weaknesses are revealed by internal scrutiny.}}
]]

Why is a SWOT analysis typically done before evaluating strategic options?
( ) 	SWOT is the best way of making strategy, so it should always be performed first. {{SWOT is a very useful tool for strategy formation, but cannot be used in isolation to create strategy. It also has its own limitations, for example it does not prioritize the listed strengths, weaknesses, opportunities or threats.}}
( ) 	A SWOT analysis creates new strategic options that would be otherwise unknown. {{SWOT is only used to better evaluate competitive options. It does not create new ones.}}
(x) 	To understand which strategic option could create the greatest competitive advantage given known strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats. {{ SWOT is a great way to identify the set of factors that affect a competitive decision.}}
( ) 	Choosing the best strategic option is easy, but you must document the process. {{Choosing a strategic option is rarely easy. Methods like SWOT are used to capture some of the complexity of such decisions.}}

As Kirk is using the SWOT analysis framework for evaluating the strategic options for his squad, he receives the following additional pieces of information to consider:

I.	Nyota, a potential candidate for one of the open positions on Kirkís squad, has significant experience with optical technology. She is currently interviewing with multiple teams

[[Strength {{Nyota is not yet part of the team, but there may be an opportunity to hire her and make her a future strength.}}
Weakness
(Opportunity)
Threat
Irrelevant
]]

II.	UFP decides the Enterprise product is the best candidate to compete with RSE.com for the upcoming government project bid. The VP gives Kirk a substantial budget increase.

[[(Strength) 
Weakness
Opportunity {{The budget has already been granted, and hence becomes an internal strength for Kirkís squad.}}
Threat
Irrelevant
]]

III.	Kirk hears of a supplier named Coruscant that designs advanced optical technology solutions. However, he finds out that this technology is incompatible with their productís requirement.

[[Strength {{Kirk can source this technology from other suppliers. Coruscantís technology, being incompatible, doesnít seem to be useful for Kirkís decision.}}
Weakness {{Kirk can source this technology from other suppliers. Coruscantís technology, being incompatible, doesnít seem to be useful for Kirkís decision.}}
Opportunity {{Kirk can source this technology from other suppliers. Coruscantís technology, being incompatible, doesnít seem to be useful for Kirkís decision.}}
Threat {{Kirk can source this technology from other suppliers. Coruscantís technology, being incompatible, doesnít seem to be useful for Kirkís decision.}}
(Irrelevant)
]]

IV.	An aggressive startup, Qon OS, has been offering high-paying jobs to experienced engineers from UFP to lure them away. Kirk believes some members of his squad may be targeted too.

[[Strength
Weakness
Opportunity
(Threat)
Irrelevant
]]

V.	Kirk discovers that successful validation of an internally developed optical technology would probably require an experienced Science officer on the team, which Kirk squad does not have. 

[[Strength
(Weakness)
Opportunity {{ While new candidates for the position may be an opportunity for the team, note that currently no candidates exist. This is an internal disadvantage that weakens the teamís position.}}
Threat
Irrelevant
]]

You have just heard that a competitor has announced it is developing a new aerospace product that the competitor claims might be better than the with one you are working on.
>>You could:<<
( )	Observe that it is the responsibility of others at your company to assess the competition.  {{Strategic thinking is not limited to those whose jobs it is to officially make strategy or assess the competitive landscape.}}
( )	Read the press release to learn what they claim and move on. {{You should not accept competitive claims at face value without verifying them.  }}
(x)	Gather the available facts and run it through a model to verify if their claims are possible. {{Critical thinking is important in strategic thinking. Critical thinking tests propositions for reality, assessing their worth or validity, by analyzing and evaluating information that has been gathered. }}


||Critical thinking is important in strategic thinking. ||

You have created a new Artificial Intelligence technology that could have a number of applications. You want to consider what product line at the company might best commercialize this technology. 
>>You could:<<
( ) Go with your intuition.   {{While intuition has a role in strategic decision making, strategic thinkers need to go beyond their past experiences, and activate their ability to imagine what else or how else things can be.}}
(x) Stimulate your creative juices and reflect on the opportunities ñ e.g. take a walk or sleep on the problem.{{Strategic thinkers need to activate their ability to imagine what how else things can be. Dealing only with intuition and/or analysis of information is insufficient. 
Creativity is important in strategic thinking.}}
( ) Look at facts and data, and analyze them to come up with an innovative product based on the technology. {{While analysis can help evaluate decisions, on its own it can promote traditional ìeither/orî thinking which can stop creative thinking. Strategic thinkers need to activate their ability to imagine what else or how else things can be.    }}


||Creativity is important in strategic thinking.  ||

You are an engineer in a company that makes smart phones. Even though your team has been releasing exciting new models on schedule, your market share has been slipping to a rival. 
>>You could:<<
(x) Talk to a range of people to get a broad perspective on the situation -  e.g. co-workers, customers, partners involved in selling, etc. {{The ability to see a situation from a broad perspective is important in strategic thinking. By diversifying and expanding your interactions you can challenge your in-built assumptions and frameworks.}}
( ) Keep doing what you are doing. You know you are building great products. Customers will catch on. {{You need to challenge your in-built assumptions and frameworks by drawing on a vast and diverse range of frames and points of view.   }}
( ) Encourage your team to promote your products in popular forums and blogs. {{This is a limited response and also assumes the problem is lack of promotion. You need to challenge your in-built assumptions and frameworks by drawing on a vast and diverse range of frames and points of view.   }}



||Taking a broad perspective is important in strategic thinking.||

You are leading a team to create a new hybrid vehicle. Your boss has handed you a mountain of data ñ on competitive products, consumer preferences, suppliers, in-house and external technologies and so on. The data is inconsistent, incomplete, and in flux.
>>You could:<<
( )	Delegate! Hand it off to a junior member of the team to summarize it for you. {{You are important in coming up with an innovative, competitive product. You need to think about how everything effects everything else.  }}
( )	Separate out what you think is important and focus on that. {{ Separating out things is not good when practising strategic thinking: in a complex world you must think about how everything effects everything else.}}
(x)	Develop an ability to comprehend many things at once, even where they are inconsistent, incomplete, and in flux. {{While this is challenging to develop, strategic thinking requires an ability to juggle, i.e. to attend to competing, incomplete and inaccurate information all at once.}}

||Juggling (i.e. attending to competing, incomplete and inaccurate information all at once) is important in strategic thinking.  ||

You are a young manager at a large consumer electronics firm who is leading its expansion into a new country. You donít have control over many uncertainties that could make or break your business strategy ñ like the local economics, politics, regulation, competitive response etc. 
>>You could:<<
(x)	Pay close attention to these things over which you have no control {{For strategic thinking it is critical to deal with things you cannot control, rather than to focus on what you can control. 
If everyone has access to the same data, those who win will be the ones coming up with creative responses to the unknown and uncontrollable. 
}}
( )	Focus on the things you can control, there is no point worrying about things that are out of your hands {{For strategic thinking it is critical to deal with things you cannot control, rather than to focus on what you can control. }}
( )	Tell your strategy team to keep them in mind while you focus on what you can control {{This may seem like the best use of your resources, but it is not. For strategic thinking it is critical to deal with things you cannot control, rather than to focus on what you can control. }}

||Dealing with things you cannot control is important in strategic thinking.  ||

You are a development engineer at a small company that provides software to analyse the home heating efficiency of newly constructed homes. You share this competitive market with a division of a major company, who has just announced a new set of features that will give them a strong advantage.
>>You could:<<
( ) Propose to the management and board a roadmap to respond{{This is good, but is there an even better response?}}
( ) Work day and night to try to build the new features{{This is inefficient, and you will burn out.}}
(x) Rally your small group, prioritize these features and try to build them in the next few weeks{{Possessing an adamant and relentless desire to win is important for strategic thinking. Rallying your team, prioritizing features and building them in a fast paced but realistic timeline is the best response. }}

||Desiring to win is important in strategic thinking.  ||

>>Strategic thinking mostly helps with identifying:<<
( ) 	Strengths {{Strategic thinking widens the solution space. You could be building upon strengths, but mainly you are looking to capitalize on another element of SWOT. Which one is it? }}
( ) 	Weaknesses {{Strategic thinking widens the solution space. You could be addressing weaknesses, but mainly you are looking to capitalize on another element of SWOT. Which one is it?}}
(x) 	Opportunities {{Strategic thinking takes a broad view of opportunities, widening the solution space}}
( ) 	Threats {{Strategic thinking widens the solution space. You could be addressing threats, but mainly you are looking to capitalize on another element of SWOT. Which one is it?}}

>>Strategic thinking relies on two skills, namely thinking:<<
( ) 	Divergently and creatively {{Thinking divergently and creatively are both widening the solution space, you also want to test propositions for their validity.}}
( )	    Fast and slow {{These are two modes of thinking, but not the two skills strategic thinking relies on ñ those two skills involve i) testing propositions for their validity, and ii) incubating new ideas}}
(X) 	Critically and creatively {{Strategic thinking relies on critical thinking and creativity. 
Critical thinking tests propositions for reality, assessing their worth or validity, by analyzing and evaluating information that has been gathered. 
Creativity forms something new and valuable, for example by incubating new ideas and bringing together different and seemingly unrelated dimensions. }}
( ) 	Convergently and critically {{Thinking convergently and critically are both focusing the solution space, you also want to creatively explore alternatives to widen the solution space.    }}

||Strategic thinking involves testing propositions for their validity as well as incubating new ideas.||

>>Strategic thinking should be practiced by:<<
( ) 	The CEO {{The CEO certainly needs to practise strategic thinking, but is there a better answer?}}
( )     The strategy team {{The CEO certainly needs to practise strategic thinking, but is there a better answer?}}
( ) 	Senior managers {{Senior managers do need to practise strategic thinking, but is there a better answer?}}
(x) 	Everyone in the organization {{Strategic thinking should be practised by everyone in the organization. 
You can contribute to your organization by developing and practicing strategic thinking.
}}
( ) 	Strategy consultants {{Strategic thinking is not just the domain of strategy consultants, is there a better answer?}}

Fill in the blank:
________________ brings together different and seemingly unrelated dimensions ñ and something new emerges. 
( ) 	Juggling {{Juggling is about dealing with ambiguity, which of the choices is about incubating new ideas?}}
(x) 	Creativity {{Creativity is the ability to form something new and valuable. It brings together different and seemingly unrelated dimensions ñ and something new emerges. }}
( ) 	Winning {{Possessing a relentless desire to win is one of the personal attributes that supports strategic thinking, but which of the choices is about incubating new ideas?}}
( ) 	Focusing {{Focusing helps in strategic planning, but which of the choices is about incubating new ideas?}}


||This is a skill that supports strategic thinking.||

>>Houbolt considered the whole mission design, including operational risk. This is an example of which personal attribute that supports strategic thinking:<<
(x) 	Keeping a broad perspective {{Keeping a broad perspective, i.e. being willing to take a wide-ranging view of facts and events, Houbolt considered the risks associated with the whole mission design, including operational risk.}}
( ) 	Juggling incomplete or inaccurate information {{Houbolt was willing to take a wide-ranging view of facts and events ñ which choice relates best to this?}}
( ) 	Dealing with things over which you have no control {{Houbolt was willing to take a wide-ranging view of facts and events ñ which choice relates best to this?}}
( ) 	Possessing a relentless desire to win {{Houbolt was willing to take a wide-ranging view of facts and events ñ which choice relates best to this?}}

||Houbolt was willing to take a wide-ranging view of facts and events ñ which choice relates best to this?||

>>Who carries influence over strategy at a company? (Select the <b>best</b> answer)<<
( ) 	The board of directors {{The board of directors may or may not influence strategy, but are not the only ones who do.}}
( ) 	The Strategy team {{A Strategy Team does formulate and communicate strategy, but is not the only one who influences it.}}
( ) 	The senior management, including business and engineering managers {{Senior management does influence strategy, but they are not the only ones who do.}}
( ) 	The investors {{Investors may or may not influence strategy at a company, and typically respond to new strategy with market actions.}}
(x) 	Any employee of the company {{Correct! Strategy is not created in a vacuum. All employees as responsible for creating new strengths or weaknesses, which influence strategy in the next business cycle.}}

You have been invited to a SWOT analysis meeting to represent your team. The management is looking for insights on what new factors to consider when making their strategy for the next year. How might you best prepare to contribute the most to this meeting?
( ) 	Read as many industry reports as possible to determine what opportunities and threats exist out there.{{This might indeed be useful, but there would be others at the meeting with this information.}}
( ) 	Conduct a SWOT analysis of your own, and report with your results.{{This is a good exercise to familiarize yourself with the process, but doesnít contribute new information.}}
(x) 	Find examples of new strengths within your own team that might influence strategy, and prepare a brief.{{Correct! By surfacing strengths (or weaknesses) that the team may not know about, you contribute the most new insights.}}
( ) 	Find the biggest weakness in your competitorís products that may be exploited in your next generation of products.{{You may be able to find such information or you may not, and others may already have it.}}

>>Which of these is the <b>best</b> example of a strength that influenced strategy?<<
( ) 	A company finds that a supplier of a key component of their products is looking to be acquired, and decides to buy the company to have better control on supply and pricing of this part.{{This is an opportunity that influenced strategy to create a new strength.}}
( ) 	A company realizes that its profits have been declining due to falling prices of competitors, and decides to focus on cost-reduction efforts to increase profitability.{{This is a response to an industry condition, an external Threat, which influenced strategy.}}
( ) 	A company finds that a large competitor is about to enter the market, and starts focusing on building loyalty with its own customer base to prevent loss of market share.{{This is a response to competitive intelligence of an external Threat that influenced a strategic decision.}}
(x) 	A company discovers that a technology developed in-house makes it easier for them to produce another set of products, and decides to enter the market for these products. {{Correct! A technology existing internally was a Strength, which led to a new strategy.}}

Since September 2015, IKEA has switched over its entire lighting range to LEDs. LED bulbs last up to 20 years and use up to 85% less energy than incandescent bulbs. 
>>What dimension of Democratic Design does this best highlight?<<
( )     Form {{LED bulbs enable customers to live more sustainable lives at home. }}
( ) 	Function {{LED bulbs enable customers to live more sustainable lives at home. }}
( ) 	Quality {{LED bulbs enable customers to live more sustainable lives at home. }}
(x) 	Sustainability {{LED bulbs enable customers to live more sustainable lives at home by using less energy, and by not having to be replaced as often as incandescent bulbs. }}
( ) 	Low Price {{LED bulbs enable customers to live more sustainable lives at home. }}


||LED bulbs are better for the planet ñ which dimension of Democratic Design values this aspect? ||

>>Factors that appear in strategy influence what products are developed at a company and which are not. Which of the below are valid factors? (Select all that apply)<<
[x] Does your product support the mission? {{ selected: Think back to the key elements of strategy. Your product needs to support the companyís mission. }}
[ ] 	Is your product in line with shareholder expectations? {{ selected: Incorrect: This is not in the key elements of strategy. Shareholders can be diverse, with different agendas, expectations and investment horizons. }}
[x] 	Does your product create competitive advantage? {{ selected: Think back to the key elements of strategy. Your product needs to create competitive advantage. }}
[x] 	Does your product align with action programs? {{ selected: Think back to the key elements of strategy. Your product needs to align with action programs.}}

||Think back to the key elements of strategy. ||

>>IKEAís ODGER chair is designed to be easy to assemble. This best illustrates:<<
( ) 	Strategy informing market and customers {{Think what the chair and its ease of assembly map to in the answer responses. }}
(x) 	Strategy informing products and features {{This best illustrates strategy informing products (a chair in this case) and features (ease of assembly in this case). }}
( ) 	Strategy informing product variants, platforms and commonality {{Think what the chair and its ease of assembly map to in the answer responses. }}
( ) 	Strategy informing how regulatory approval will be obtained {{Think what the chair and its ease of assembly map to in the answer responses. }}

||Think what the chair and its ease of assembly map to in the answer responses. ||

>>If youíre an engineer on a product team, you should:<<
( ) 	Focus entirely on your product and leave understanding business strategy to the CEO and strategy team {{Your companyís strategy directly impacts your product, so you should not be leaving its understanding to the CEO and strategy team. }}
( ) 	Understand business strategy broadly but primarily focus on the product you are working on {{Good but not enough - you need to know your companyís strategy well enough to trace the alignment of your product with strategy.}}
(x) 	Understand business strategy well enough to be able to trace its key elements to the products you are working on {{Excellent! You need to know your companyís strategy well enough to trace the alignment of your product with strategy.}}

||Your companyís strategy directly influences your product. ||

>>IKEA is able to charge low prices by using a variety of methods to reduce costs. Which of the following methods is it <strong>least likely</strong> to use?<<
( ) 	Forming long term relationships with suppliers {{This can help keep input costs low. }}
(x) 	Switching out expensive packing material for cheap non-recyclable Styrofoam packing material {{While this may reduce costs, using non-recyclable packing material goes against the ëSustainabilityí dimension of Democratic Design.}}
( ) 	Manufacturing in low cost countries{{This is a way IKEA can keep costs low.}}
( ) 	Developing products directly on the factory floor, by having designers work closely with production specialists {{This optimizes designs and helps IKEA keep costs low.}}
( ) 	Developing products that can be flat-packed {{This reduces storage and transport costs.}}


||You should pick the cost reduction method that is least consistent with IKEAís dimensions of Democratic Design. ||

What is true of everything that could be considered a product in this list?
( )  They are all exchanged for money, directly or indirectly {{Products may not be exchanged for money necessarily.}}
( )  They are all created by profit-driven organizations{{Products can be created by any kind of organization, or by an individual.}}
(x)  They all create some kind of ëvalueí for someone by addressing a need {{ All products eventually create value}}
( )  They all technical in nature {{ Products need not be, and are often not, technical. An example of this would be most services.}}

Consider a truck manufacturing company. Using the definition of a product, classify each of the following as either an output, a method of transfer or exchange, or a value that is created.

I.	Trucks being assembled at a manufacturing plant
[[Method or Transfer
Value Created
(Output - Good or Service){{From the perspective of the plant, the assembled truck is something that is produced as an output. It is not a method of transfer or a value in itself.}}
]]

II.	A purchasing agreement between an automotive company and a transportation company
[[(Method or Transfer ){{A purchasing agreement is what creates a sale, and thus causes the product to be exchanged. It is not an output or a value in itself.}}
Value Created
Output - Good or Service
]]

III.	The movement of an item from its source to the destination where it is needed
[[Method or Transfer
(Value Created) {{The movement of an item from source to destination is the ultimate value created for the person using the truck. Thus, it is not an output or a method of exchange.}}
Output - Good or Service
]]

>>Which of the below statements about value is <strong>false</strong>?<<
( ) 	Better value comes from larger benefit and/or smaller cost {{Value is benefit at cost. Larger benefit and/or smaller cost do thus increase the value, so this statement is true. Which statement is false?}}
(x) 	Value can be objectively defined {{Value cannot be objectively defined. It depends on the subjective opinions of the individuals involved in producing, transferring, and using the product. }}
( ) 	Value depends on the individuals involved in producing, transferring, and using the product {{Value depends on the subjective opinions of the individuals involved in producing, transferring, and using the product, so this statement is true. Which statement is false?}}
( ) 	Worse value comes from smaller benefit and/or larger cost {{Value is benefit at cost. Smaller benefit and/or larger cost do thus decrease the value, so this statement is true. Which statement is false?}}

||Value is benefit at cost.||

>>Who is in the strongest position to judge value?<<
( ) 	The producer who creates the product {{The producer does not operate the product, think of who unleashes the benefit of the product. }}
( ) 	The customer who arranges the exchange / is the middle-man between the producer and the user {{The customer is not the user in this case and does not operate the product, think of who unleashes the benefit of the product.}}
(x) 	The user who operates the product {{The user operates the product and unleashes the benefit of the product. The user is in the strongest position to judge value.}}
( ) 	Experts who review the product {{They do not operate the product routinely, think of who routinely unleashes the benefit of the product.}}


||Who unleashes the benefit of the product?||

You want to develop an understanding of what the user of your product views as value and how your product creates that value. 
>>What could you do?<<
( ) 	Talk to the users {{Yes, but are any of the other options also valid? }}
( ) 	Watch users work with your products {{Yes, but are any of the other options also valid? }}
( ) 	Do demonstrations of your products {{Yes, but are any of the other options also valid? }}
( ) 	Let users interact with prototypes {{Yes, but are any of the other options also valid? }}
(x) 	All of the above {{These are all great ways to develop an understanding of what the user of your product views as value and how your product creates that value. }}


||Think of the different ways you could gain an understanding of what the user of your product views as value and how your product creates that value.  ||

Recall that a product is an output that is exchanged and <strong>produces a value</strong>. If we think about products as systems, then what property of a system is responsible for producing value?

( ) 	The entities {{Entities do not produce value in themselves. They are what a system is composed of, and may be essential to its behavior, but a system is more than the sum of its parts.}}
( ) 	The relationships {{The relationships are not the source of value in themselves. They simply describe how each entity relates to another. }}
( ) 	The complexity {{Complexity is a commonly seen property of systems and is important to manage, but it is not the source of value.}}
( ) 	The architecture {{The architecture of a system is valuable from the perspective of a designer, but does not directly produce value.}}
(x) 	The emergent function(s) {{Correct! Function emerges from a system, and it is what produces value for the systemís user.}}

System success occurs when:
( ) All the entities are working {{This is necessary but not sufficient.  Systems can fail even when all their entities are working, because of unexpected or dysfunctional interactions or failure in accompanying systems.}}
( ) Management says it was a success {{This is not a necessary nor sufficient criterion of system success. }}
(x) The desired value is delivered {{This is a necessary and sufficient way of defining when system success occurs, i.e. when the desired value is delivered. }}
( ) The accompanying systems are working {{This is necessary but not sufficient. Systems can fail when the accompanying systems are working, e.g. due to their entities failing or due to unexpected interactions. }}





||Which of the options is both necessary and sufficient for defining when system success occurs?||

Systems could fail because of:
( ) Component failure {{Yes, but could any of the other options also cause system failure? }}
( ) Unexpected interaction among elements {{Yes, but could any of the other options also cause system failure? }}
( ) Failure of an accompanying system to deliver {{Yes, but could any of the other options also cause system failure? }}
(x) All of the above {{These are all valid ways in which systems could fail. System suppliers may be held responsible for all these kinds of failures and must anticipate and pre-empt these.  }}


||Is there more than one way that systems could fail?||

>>Which is the most powerful tool of system building that should be applied to building products?<<
( ) 	Simulation {{While simulations can be useful when building certain product systems, think about a tool that can be applied to all products that are systems. }}
(x) 	Decomposition {{All product systems can be decomposed ñ broken into entities small enough that humans can understand, develop and operate them. Decomposition allows us to divide and conquer.}}
( ) 	Decision making under uncertainty {{While this is a useful technique in systems thinking, think about a tool that can be applied to all products that are systems. }}
( ) 	Optimization  {{While this can be a useful technique in certain cases, think about a tool that can be applied to all products that are systems. }}


|| Which of these tools helps us divide and conquer when building products. ||

>>Which is the most powerful tool of system building that should be applied to building products?<<
( ) 	Simulation {{While simulations can be useful when building certain product systems, think about a tool that can be applied to all products that are systems. }}
(x) 	Decomposition {{All product systems can be decomposed ñ broken into entities small enough that humans can understand, develop and operate them. Decomposition allows us to divide and conquer.}}
